  <title>Chemical Kinetics I</title>

  <p> <em>Reaction Rates and Stoichiometry.</em> First, we define reaction rate
    and note the dependence of rates of change in concentration on reaction
    stoichiometry. </p>

  <p>
      <ul>
      <li>We distinguish between <term>instantaneous rate</term> (<m>d[]/dt</m>) and <term>average rate</term> (<m>\Delta []/\Delta t</m>).</li>
      <li>Rates of consumption (reactants) and production (products) depend on the stoichiometry of the reaction.
        Species with higher stoichiometric coefficients are consumed (produced) more rapidly!</li>
      <li><term>Standard rate</term> ("rate") is the concentration of reaction occurrences ("reactions") per unit time.</li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <p>
    <image source="14-1-conc-time-graph.png" width="90%">A plot of the concentrations of A, B, and C over time according to the reaction A plus 2 B goes to 3 C.</image>    
  </p>

  <p>
    Relations between instantaneous rates of consumption and production:
  </p>
  <p>
    <m>-\frac{1}{1} \frac{d[\ce{A}]}{dt} = -\frac{1}{2} \frac{d[\ce{B}]}{dt} = +\frac{1}{3} \frac{d[\ce{C}]}{dt}</m>
  </p>
  
